---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import JsonFormatterIsland from '../../islands/JsonFormatterIsland'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('json-formatter')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <JsonFormatterIsland client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Paste your raw JSON string into the input area and click <strong>Format</strong> to instantly
        pretty-print it with proper indentation and syntax highlighting. The formatter validates your
        JSON at the same time, so any syntax errors are flagged immediately with a clear error message
        pointing to the offending line.
      </p>
      <p>
        Common use cases include debugging API responses, reviewing configuration files such as
        <code>package.json</code> or <code>tsconfig.json</code>, and cleaning up minified JSON
        before committing it to version control. You can also use the <strong>Minify</strong> button
        to compact formatted JSON back to a single line — handy when you need to embed it in an
        environment variable or HTTP request body.
      </p>
      <p>
        All processing happens entirely in your browser. Nothing is sent to a server, so you can
        safely paste credentials, API keys, or any other sensitive data without privacy concerns.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Is it safe to paste sensitive JSON data here?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Yes. This JSON formatter runs entirely client-side using JavaScript in your browser. No
          data is transmitted to any server, so passwords, tokens, and private configuration values
          never leave your machine.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the maximum JSON size this tool can handle?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          There is no hard-coded size limit. Performance depends on your device's available memory
          and the browser's JavaScript engine. In practice, JSON files up to several megabytes format
          in well under a second on modern hardware.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How do I validate JSON online without installing anything?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Paste your JSON into this tool and click Format. If the JSON is invalid, the tool displays
          a parse error with the line and column number so you can locate and fix the problem
          immediately.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the difference between pretty-print and minified JSON?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Pretty-printed JSON adds newlines and indentation to make the structure readable for
          humans. Minified JSON removes all unnecessary whitespace to reduce file size, which lowers
          network transfer time for APIs and reduces storage footprint.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
